==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|pleden|lang=enm}}, {{term|plaiden|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|fro}} {{term|lang=fro|plaider||to plead, offer a plea}}, from {{term|lang=fro|plait}}, from {{etyl|ML.}} {{term|lang=la|placitum||a decree, sentence, suit, plea, etc.", in Classical {{etyl|la}}, "an opinion, determination, prescription, order; literally, that which is pleasing, pleasure}}, neuter of {{term|lang=la|placitus}}, past participle of {{term|lang=la|placere||to please}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|/ˈpliːd/}}
* {{audio|en-us-plead.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|iːd}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb|pleads|pleading|'''[[pled]]''' {{qualifier|North America, Scotland}} or '''[[pleaded]]''' {{qualifier|England}}}}

# To present an argument, especially in a legal case.
#: {{usex|The defendant has decided to '''plead''' not guilty.}}
# To beg, beseech, or implore.
#: {{usex|He '''pleaded''' with me not to leave the house.}}

